---
import BaseHead from "../components/BaseHead.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import { SITE_TITLE } from "../consts";
---

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead
			title={`About — ${SITE_TITLE}`}
			description="Learn about Veilus, the open-source anti-detect browser built on a custom Chromium engine."
		/>
		<style>
			.about-content {
				max-width: 65ch;
			}
			.about-content h1 {
				margin-bottom: 1em;
			}
			.about-content h2 {
				margin-top: 2em;
				margin-bottom: 0.5em;
				color: var(--accent);
				font-size: 1.4em;
			}
			.about-content p {
				margin-bottom: 1.25em;
				color: var(--text-primary);
			}
			.about-content a {
				color: var(--accent);
			}
			.community-links {
				display: flex;
				flex-wrap: wrap;
				gap: 1em;
				margin-top: 1em;
				list-style: none;
				padding: 0;
			}
			.community-links li a {
				display: inline-block;
				padding: 0.5em 1em;
				border: 1px solid var(--border);
				border-radius: 8px;
				text-decoration: none;
				font-family: "Inter", sans-serif;
				font-weight: 600;
				font-size: 0.9em;
				transition: border-color 0.15s ease, color 0.15s ease;
			}
			.community-links li a:hover {
				border-color: var(--accent);
			}
		</style>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<div class="about-content">
				<h1>About Veilus</h1>

				<h2>What is Veilus</h2>
				<p>
					Veilus is an open-source anti-detect browser built on
					Chromium. Unlike existing solutions that rely on JavaScript
					injection to mask browser fingerprints, Veilus modifies the
					browser at the engine level — providing native fingerprint
					management that's fundamentally harder to detect.
				</p>

				<h2>Why We Built It</h2>
				<p>
					Existing anti-detect solutions are expensive, closed-source,
					and use detectable JS injection techniques. We believe
					privacy tools should be transparent, community-driven, and
					built on solid engineering foundations. Veilus is our answer
					to that.
				</p>

				<h2>Open Source ⭐</h2>
				<p>
					Veilus is 100% open source. Every line of code is auditable.
					No other anti-detect browser offers this level of
					transparency. We believe trust must be earned through
					verifiable code, not marketing promises.
				</p>
				<p>
					Check out our code on <a
						href="https://github.com/nicholasgriffintn/veilus"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a
					>.
				</p>

				<h2>Contributing</h2>
				<p>
					We welcome contributors! Whether you're interested in C++
					Chromium internals, fingerprint research, or web development
					— there's a place for you. Check our <a
						href="https://docs.veilus.io"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer">development setup guide</a
					>
					and <a
						href="https://github.com/nicholasgriffintn/veilus"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub repos</a
					> to get started.
				</p>

				<h2>Community</h2>
				<p>Join the conversation and stay updated:</p>
				<ul class="community-links">
					<li>
						<a
							href="https://t.me/veilusbrowser"
							target="_blank"
							rel="noopener noreferrer">Telegram</a>
					</li>
					<li>
						<a
							href="https://x.com/veilusbrowser"
							target="_blank"
							rel="noopener noreferrer">X (Twitter)</a>
					</li>
					<li>
						<a
							href="https://github.com/nicholasgriffintn/veilus"
							target="_blank"
							rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>
					</li>
				</ul>

				<h2>This Blog</h2>
				<p>
					This blog shares technical insights, product updates, and
					guides for the Veilus community. We write about browser
					fingerprinting, privacy engineering, Chromium internals, and
					the journey of building an open-source anti-detect browser.
				</p>
			</div>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
